PS: I tracked a few items that are not above, which I later realized are more "REWARDS", or the thing you are doing the VERB for:

1. CONSOLE an NPC that is in grief
2. CONVINCE an NPC to agree with you
3. DISTRACT an NPC
4. ESCAPE from a threat
5. Gain a FAVOR
6. FIND something
7. Gain a GOAL (something to do)
8. LEARN information
9. MAKE A FRIEND
10. CATCH/TRAP a threat

We will talk about REWARDS and how they relate to VERBS later.

## Verbiage

The final VERBS I found are (in order of frequency):

1. TALK
2. SEARCH
3. EXPLORE
4. RUN AWAY
5. HELP
6. WANDER
7. HIDE
8. PERFOM
9. SOLVE PUZZLE/MYSTERY/RIDDLE
10. ATTACK (Ineffectual)
11. SNEAK/SPY
12. USE
13. PLAN
14. STEAL
15. CHASE
16. HAVE A MEAL
17. PLAY

Some of these only appear a few times in comparison to some of the others. Others are obviously less _mechanical_ VERBS (i.e. dice rolling), and more just role-playing (players talking it through), so lets take out: TALK, HELP, SOLVE PUZZLE, PLAN, HAVE A MEAL, PLAY.

These VERBS are what the players may describe their characters doing, or act out as their characters. Adding dice mechanics here may unnecessary crunch.

We are left with:

1. SEARCH
2. EXPLORE
3. RUN AWAY
5. WANDER
6. HIDE
7. PERFORM
8. ATTACK (Ineffectual)
9. SNEAK/SPY
10. USE
11. STEAL
12. CHASE

Let's group these together and analyze.

## People

The most common VERB is TALK, which can be grouped with many of the other "role-playing" VERBS as "interacting with NPCs". These NPCs have their own wants, needs, and goals outside of the player characters and should be role-played as such. This gives a reactive push-back to the player's actions, something that adds meaning to what the PCs are doing.

Many games add rules for talking to NPCs to sway them to your side or to tease information out of them (e.g. 5e's Deception, Insight, and Persuasion checks). I don't like this, as a dice failure (random chance) which seldom leads to clear negatives. Maybe the NPC gets angry? But at the end of the day, it feels a little contrived.

I think that PERFORM is slightly different. The PCs are trying to entertain the NPCs in some way, often a crowd. This could be singing a song (as is often in Over the Garden Wall) but I can easily see giving a speech or performing some kind of stunt in the same vain. This could result in a bonus to another roll (or a negative if they fail), but could also have a big impact on the NPC reactions one way or another.

HELP is in a similar vein. The specifics could fall into a wide variety of tasks, but boils down to "helping an NPC achieve their goal". This should result in some REWARD. I don't know if this VERB calls for a over-arching dice mechanic, we shall see.

As mentioned in [a better blog](http://falsemachine.blogspot.com/2020/05/soft-ass-d.html) serving food or HAVING A MEAL with someone is a great way to MAKE A FRIEND. It is an intimate activity not shared lightly, and presents a good diegetic opportunity to TALK. The same goes for PLAY, especially for younger characters. If you ever have the opportunity (without seeming creepy), watch children playing in a park. Two kids who might be total strangers will expend a lot of energy together just having fun, perhaps for hours, and maybe not even learn each other's names.

REWARDS: CONSOLE, CONVINCE, DISTRACT, FAVOR, GOAL, LEARN, MAKE A FRIEND

## Things

After TALK, the two most common VERBS are SEARCH and EXPLORE, which one can call "interacting with the environment". The PCs are actively engaging with the environment, either with a specific goal (SEARCH) or just to scope out an area (EXPLORE). I believe that this should not always require a roll, only if there is a benefit to be gained (e.g. gain an item) or if there are high stakes to failure (e.g. ticking clock). Information should almost always just be given, no roll required.

If the players are moving but are not actively EXPLORING, then they WANDER. This might be described as moving from one point to another with no goal along the way, just to reach their destination. You can correlate this with most "travel" rules in other TTRPGs, where random encounters can happen; there are no clear apparent threats along the route, but who knows what will happen?

Another part of the "environment" are the items the PCs pick up along the way. The can be USED to create a benefit in achieving another goal (e.g. throw candy at the dog to DISTRACT it, ring the bell to SOLVE THE PUZZLE of the evil spirit). This might result in the item being "used up". Since we are avoiding combat, traditional weapons, armor, shields etc. should be less prevalent; makeshift weapons should be the norm rather than just always walking around with a sword. The PCs are not threatening.

REWARDS: FIND, LEARN

## Threats

Just because we are looking to remove combat as a core mechanic, that does not mean we are removing danger! From from it! I think that threats become a lot more interesting when you cannot just whack them with a stick, but instead need to think your way into creating opportunities and leveraging those opportunities. Of course you _can_ just ATTACK, but I want to make that a last, desperate resort that is unlikely to kill or even harm the threat, just DISTRACT it enough to then do something else.

When in doubt, RUN AWAY and HIDE. This removes you from the threat without needing to deal with it entirely. The other verbs, such as USE, can create DISTRACTIONS that help you RUN AWAY. This is the fourth highest verb from Over the Garden Wall, so some kind of mechanics makes sense; we expect the PCs to RUN AWAY a lot, so let's make it fun.

HIDING has a bit of a STEALTH to it. It could be the result of RUNNING AWAY or a way to avoid it. 
Sometimes, however, the PCs are the ones who are CHASING. This could be because someone else (probably smaller) has something they want and is high-tailing it, or perhaps they are chasing down an antagonist for some other goal, not necessarily knowing what they will do if they catch them! We could maybe use the same rules for RUN AWAY and CHASE, just inverted. The goal of a CHASE would probably be to CATCH/TRAP, and maybe lead into STEAL.

If an antagonist has an item the PCs want, they will probably try to STEAL it for themselves. This could be actively opposed (both parties aware of the attempt) or unopposed (the current owner is unaware that someone is trying to nick their stuff). Maybe slightly different mechanics depending?
Physical items are not the only thing that PCs would want from a threat, however, as information is sometimes (often) more valuable. Being SNEAKY and SPYING on the enemy can yield much information to LEARN that can then be used to create an opportunity later. This ties in with HIDING into STEALTH, so maybe one mechanic for both?

This is obviously the area I need to think on the most, for now. These will probably be the VERBS that come up during the most high-energy parts of a game session, so the mechanics should be tight, unambiguous and, most importantly, fun.

REWARDS: DISTRACT, ESCAPE, LEARN, CATCH/TRAP
